how whaling fundamentally disrupted ocean ecosystems, examine the various roles whales play in food webs, and discuss the continuing ecological chain reactions to the depletion of these large animals. In addition to reviewing what is known of the current and historic whale populations, Whales, Whaling, and Ocean Ecosystems considers how this knowledge will bear on scientific approaches to conservation and whaling in the future and provocatively asks whether it is possible to restore ocean ecosystems to their pre-whaling condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgriculture. 0aHuman ecologyxStudy and teaching. 0aMarine ecology. 0aWhales. 0aWhaling. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Oceanography.2bisacsh1 aBrownell, Robert L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDeMaster, Douglas P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoak, Daniel F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEstes, James A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Terrie M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520933200.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles